  "prompt": "What is the W boson?",
  "response": "The W boson is an elementary subatomic particle that plays a crucial role in the weak nuclear force, one of the four fundamental forces of nature. Here are key details about the W boson:\n\n1. Fundamental Properties:\n- It is a vector boson\n- Carries weak nuclear force interactions\n- Has electric charge (either positive or negative)\n- Massive particle (about 80 GeV/c\u00b2)\n- Short-lived, existing for extremely brief moments\n\n2. Types:\n- W+ (positively charged)\n- W- (negatively charged)\n\n3. Role in Physics:\n- Mediates radioactive decay\n- Crucial in nuclear processes\n- Involved in particle interactions that change particle flavors\n- Part of the electroweak theory in the Standard Model of particle physics\n\n4. Discovery:\n- Predicted theoretically in the 1960s\n- Experimentally discovered at CERN in 1983\n- Nobel Prize in Physics awarded to Carlo Rubbia and Simon van der Meer for this discovery\n\n5. Scientific Significance:\n- Important for understanding fundamental particle interactions\n- Helps explain how subatomic particles transform and interact\n- Critical to understanding nuclear processes and particle physics",
